        <div class="panel-body">
          <p><b>Plaza Maria Pita</b></p>
          <p>The Maria Pita square is La Coruña's main city plaza and takes its name from the town's heroine, Maria Pita who played a critical role in reducing the losses during the English assault on the city in 1589.  The Plaza is surrounded by typical galeria style terraced buildings as well as a variety of restaurants.  There are often performances within the Plaza.  Plaza Maria Pita is a good landmark for finding your way around the old city.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.turismocoruna.com/web/corTurServer.php?idSecweb=245&id_secPadre=217&idInfo=104"><b>Monte San Pedro</b></a></p>
          <p>Monte San Pedro provides the best views of La Coruña and the surrounding area.  The Mirador San Pedro provides a Michelin rated restaurant experience from which to enjoy these views.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.torredeherculesacoruna.com/index.php?l=en"><b>Torre de Hercules</b></a></p>
          <p>The Tower of Hercules, a UNESCO world heritage site, has served as a continuously functioning lighthouse and landmark at the entrance of La Coruña harbour in north-western Spain since the late 1st century A.D. when the Romans built the Farum Brigantium.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.coruna.gal/cultura/es/espacios/detalle-para-entidad/museo-arqueologico-castillo-de-san-anton/entidad/1149055937727"><b>Castelo San Anton</b></a></p>
          <p>The museum sits on an old fortress constructed in the XVI century. From the XVI century to XVIII century it was a defense building and prison, later it was used as a lazaret to quarantine mariners who arived in the city with infectious diseases.  The museum houses archaeological objects such as: protohistoric silverwear, megalithism, Bronze Age, Castro Culture, romanisation and different aspects of the city.</p>
        </div>
