          Out of Town
        </div>
        <div class="panel-body">
          <p><a href="http://www.catedraldesantiago.es/en"><b>Catedral de Santiago de Compostela</b></a></p>
          <p>Galicia's most famous landmark, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, approximately an hour from La Coruña by train or car.  Begun in 1075, this Romanesque and Baroque cathedral is the second most visited Catholic pilgrimage site in Europe.  In 2014 approximately 200,000 people completed the pilgrimage to this cathedral, of at the longest 500 miles, to receive their plenary indulgence.   The movie The Way with Martin Sheen is an example of this pilgrimage.  St. James the Apostle, who in theory is buried here, also happens to be the patron saint of the area, and his scallop shell symbol can be seen throughout. The nearby Parador de Santiago de Compostela serves as an extravagant final hotel stop for many tired pilgrims and is located in the same square.  The city itself is the capital of Galicia.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.caminomyway.com/camino-finisterre-spain-visiting-the-end-of-the-world"><b>Finisterre</b></a></p>
          <p>Finisterre was considered the end of the earth by Europeans until the travels of Christopher Columbus.  Some pilgrims continue past Santiago de Compostela to Finisterre, where they burn their shoes and clothes as a final ritual.  There is also a lighthouse located at this point.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.turismo.gal/presentacion-de-ourense?langId=en_US"><b>Thermal Baths of Ourense</b></a></p>
          <p>The city of Ourense is located south of La Coruña in Galicia.  It takes approximately 2 hours by car and 1.5 hours by train to reach the city.  This city is famous for its natural hot springs which flank the river of Miño as well as its ancient Roman bridges. There are various hot springs available for free use by the public.  There are also spas of varying prices, my favorite of which is Termas da Chavasqueira.  This city is generally much warmer than other areas of Galicia.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.riasbaixaswines.com/"><b>Rias Baixas</b></a></p>
          <p>Rias Baixas is home to 20,000 vineyards which mainly produce a specific type of white wine, Albariño.  There is the option to tour vineyards in this area as well as enjoy wines at local festivals and restaurants.  Rias Baixas is accessible by car and is about 1.5 hours south of La Coruña.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.spain.info/en_US/reportajes/las_divinas_islas_cies.html"><b>Islas Cies</b></a></p>
          <p>These islands, which are also nature reserves, boast some of the best beaches in the world.  They can only be reached by boat and provide very little in the way of touristic beach comforts.  There are ferries that leave for Vigo however there is a limit to the amount of people allowed on the island so you may want to book ahead.  Camping is also available.  Vigo is about 1.5 hours south of La Coruña by car or train.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.playadecatedrales.com/"><b>Playa de Las Catedrales</b></a></p>
          <p>Catedrales Beach is considered one of the best beaches in Galicia and is located in the area of Lugo, 1.5 hours from La Coruña by car.  Famous for its arching rock formations, you may have seen pictures of it before.</p>
          <br>
          <p><a href="http://www.turismo.gal/parque-natural-fragas-do-eume-presentacion?langId=en_US"><b>Fragas do Eume</b></a></p>
          <p>This 9,000 hectare natural park offers hiking of some of the best preserved forests in Europe as well as fishing.  It is about 45 minutes by car from La Coruña.</p>
